{
  "explanation": "The defendant committed a significant breach of trust by embezzling $25,000 from their employer, abusing their fiduciary position as an accountant. While white-collar crimes require a term of incarceration to serve as a deterrent and to emphasize the seriousness of stealing from an employer, the court must also heavily weigh the mitigating factors present in this case. The defendant has no prior criminal record, demonstrating that this behavior is an aberration rather than a pattern. Furthermore, the defendant has already made efforts to partially pay back the stolen funds, showing remorse and a willingness to make the victim whole. Balancing the need for accountability with the defendant's potential for rehabilitation, a short term of incarceration is warranted, followed by probation and a strict order to complete full restitution.",
  "verdict": 6
}
